WEBVTT

00:02.220 --> 00:08.520
Should the dean be bound by the majority vote of the 
department heads? Oh, no, no. It's the same type

00:10.740 --> 00:12.221
thing. You don't want a weak dean. In fact, I'd say 
that with pages. You want a dean that will not only

00:18.380 --> 00:22.640
stand up to his department heads but stand up to the 
upper administration. And I think anybody like

00:25.560 --> 00:30.600
that has got to be willing to step down any time. I

00:30.580 --> 00:41.860
mean, there are some things that are worth that. 
Looking back now over half century almost, well,

00:42.380 --> 00:48.750
half century, can you think of some opportunities 
that we at A&M in engineering that we missed, we

00:49.450 --> 00:56.990
passed by? Well, one, well, there's a couple. 
Well, one of the things I wanted to do, and I

01:00.610 --> 01:05.950
couldn't get Prescott to help, and I couldn't

01:06.090 --> 01:12.310
support it, and I believe he was, yeah, he was up 
there then. Well, there's a polymer group, and we

01:13.450 --> 01:19.710
should be strong in polymers at Texas A&M because 
this whole Gulf Coast is in the business of making

01:19.690 --> 01:23.390
polymers. I don't care how many Nobel people type 
you got. We need some people working on the

01:29.100 --> 01:33.760
chemistry that's going on in Texas. And I don't 
think we've got very much of that going on. We need,

01:37.100 --> 01:39.520
that's one of the things that we still need. That's 
still an opportunity. But the whole group wanted

01:42.730 --> 01:45.710
to move down here. From where? Massachusetts. The 
University of Massachusetts, I recall. And we had

01:53.650 --> 01:58.950
it all lined up, Benson and I, and we couldn't get 
support for it. Another one I think the university

01:59.570 --> 02:01.670
missed, they're always trying to bring people 
into this system. One of the schools that they

02:05.090 --> 02:06.870
didn't bring in, they should have been on the bus. 
They were on the ball. And I told Thompson so. I

02:10.850 --> 02:13.110
think it was too late. It was Lamar Tech. Lamar Tech 
is an engineering school like A&M, a good location

02:14.770 --> 02:20.150
on the coast. And is a school that fits with A&M 
better. It got into this, I told him, even though

02:24.290 --> 02:27.670
it's in the other bunch, it doesn't have to stay in 
there. The people in Lamar Tech would much prefer

02:28.850 --> 02:33.510
to be in our system than in theirs because there's 
more to be gained. We've got a lot of synergisms

02:35.730 --> 02:37.750
that you don't have. with a bunch of teacher 
schools. They got in with Sam Houston and some

02:39.330 --> 02:42.170
others. But there's one opportunity that we've 
missed there, and they've gotten in a lot of others

02:47.330 --> 02:52.020
that I don't know whether there were 
opportunities or not. They may go the other way,

02:52.000 --> 02:53.940
but that's one that ought to be pursued now. Did we 
miss on any scholars that you can think of, any

03:00.120 --> 03:06.080
faculty that we might have gotten? Oh, I don't know 
that we did.

03:10.560 --> 03:14.900
I'm not sure that we might have offered the one or 
two that we didn't get. But you can't think of any

03:16.260 --> 03:20.200
that became really great. Would have made the 
difference. One of the things that I think that

03:22.800 --> 03:26.660
another thing that I think is a real issue is that 
universities want to buy their standing. They go

03:36.760 --> 03:39.460
around hiring everybody else's people. I think a 
real credit to the university is did we grow

03:41.440 --> 03:44.320
people? And I think that there's no mark ever given 
for how many people did you grow on your faculty,

03:47.860 --> 03:50.580
bringing them up from assistant professor to 
where they became people of stature. And that

03:55.353 --> 03:58.500
really should be the mark of a university is, did 
you grow them yourself, or did you just put the

03:58.480 --> 04:01.320
money out and get them? Anybody can buy anything if 
they got the money. Who's the old boy that's got

04:06.480 --> 04:07.961
CNN? He can buy it. But I think there's not enough. 
There's not enough credit given, and I don't ever

04:11.440 --> 04:13.780
hear that mentioned, is did you develop these 
people? Now, in a company, that's a real mark. They

04:23.320 --> 04:26.920
don't go and get their people from somebody else. 
Did you ever have, or do you now have, any

04:26.900 --> 04:32.900
department of chemical engineering elsewhere 
after whom you wanted us to be modeled? No. I don't

04:40.800 --> 04:45.580
think we ought to be looking at somebody else. 
That's the trouble. What we ought to do is look at

04:47.160 --> 04:50.880
the state of Texas, the industry that we have, and 
then model ourselves to serve the people that we

04:56.460 --> 04:59.840
are set up to serve. And I think trying to be like 
somebody else, unless they've got the same

05:03.300 --> 05:07.260
situation we are, we are unique, we've got the A&M 
in the name, and we ought to go ahead and pull

05:07.240 --> 05:10.140
through on these other things. Yeah. Like your 
alma mater at NC State, they are very good in

05:17.640 --> 05:18.885
textile. Yeah. Well, that was a whole area, 
textile. That fits with that state. It fits with

05:22.500 --> 05:23.781
the state. Yeah. And we hear a downgrade in 
agriculture some. I think that, I was talking to

05:27.240 --> 05:30.620
one of the people in agriculture, and I think his 
old Harry was wanting to say, well, you don't need

05:32.960 --> 05:33.981
all this. One guy said, well, hell, I guess you'd 
get one cow and one hog and teach agriculture. But I

05:37.560 --> 05:39.580
think agriculture is a big part of it. I think 
agriculture is a big part of it. I think

05:40.560 --> 05:42.420
agriculture is a big thing, and it still is a big 
thing in the state, and will continue to be. It may

05:44.500 --> 05:47.420
be a different type of agriculture, it may be very 
intensive type, but you've got all the different

05:47.400 --> 05:52.660
type industries that we've got here, and we need to 
be, we've got the electronic industry and so on,

05:56.440 --> 05:59.840
but we've also got the big chemical industry, and 
we'll still, this chemical industry is not going

06:03.000 --> 06:04.021
away. In fact, I'm writing an article right here 
now, a study that we did. It's saying that actually

06:08.584 --> 06:13.060
the 20th and 21st century should be called the 
chemical age, because you can't look anywhere and

06:13.040 --> 06:17.080
see any material that wasn't in some way touched by 
the chemical industry. You might say, well, the

06:20.769 --> 06:23.520
information age and all of this. Well, actually, 
that's just come from a calculator that's made out

06:25.920 --> 06:28.500
of chips, which is a chemical product. So all of 
those are really subsets of the chemical. What

06:30.920 --> 06:34.660
we've really done is bring on all these new 
materials that have made life a lot better, and

06:34.640 --> 06:38.940
have made possible all these other things. They 
look like they're the thing that's driving it, and

06:41.133 --> 06:45.700
they do have an upper hand right now, but you've got 
to have all these things, and people are not going

06:49.460 --> 06:51.900
to do without them, and they're still going to be 
coming, more and more of them, and what's

06:54.320 --> 06:58.960
happening is that the life sciences is really, 
they're recognizing that they're just

06:58.940 --> 07:02.540
chemistry, and as they learn the chemistry and 
cancer and all of this, they're going to be able to

07:05.920 --> 07:08.860
better understand and treat all these things as 
well as the chemicals produce better foods. So

07:11.300 --> 07:15.240
some of these companies are separating 
themselves into life sciences and chemicals, and

07:15.220 --> 07:19.540
I think that's a mistake because one of these days 
they're going to need a life, what they might refer

07:19.520 --> 07:23.200
to as a biological process, but all they're doing 
is carrying out a chemical reaction right next to

07:25.980 --> 07:29.860
another one that they regard as a chemical 
reaction. So I think that's the direction that

07:30.507 --> 07:33.460
we're going to go in. They'll come back together. 
Right now they're going apart, but they'll come

07:35.020 --> 07:38.440
back together. And so I see the chemical as being a 
big thing from now on. Am I correct that you appear

07:45.180 --> 07:50.580
to be defining chemical engineering as applied 
chemistry? Chemistry in the real world that

07:51.711 --> 07:54.700
serves a purpose? Yeah. Let's see, as you went out 
to either search for funding for chemical

07:56.448 --> 08:04.060
engineering research or to work more on chemical 
engineering, what did you do? I did a lot of

08:06.620 --> 08:07.641
research. I did a lot of research. I worked more 
closely with some of our alumni and so forth. Do you

08:13.710 --> 08:23.630
have any stories of the real world of how those 
people felt about A&M and about the chemical

08:23.610 --> 08:25.310
engineering here? Oh,

08:25.290 --> 08:32.980
I'm not, it's been a long time since I've, I did go 
with them the other day though, and old Charles

08:32.960 --> 08:37.920
Herter, just a surprising thing. I taught him, and 
it's a good thing I continued to teach because he

08:37.900 --> 08:41.620
graduated around the same time I graduated, 
around 72. And you know, Les Appelt, he is now the

08:43.320 --> 08:50.340
president and chief executive officer of that 
company. And he was a chemical engineer, and the

08:50.320 --> 08:56.120
reason he's done so well is that he can judge 
commercial projects. And so he's at the very top of

08:57.309 --> 09:01.420
it, and I went with old Legetti and him down there to 
hunt some money. And I hadn't really had much to do

09:03.190 --> 09:08.920
with him since he graduated. I'd met him once other 
time. And, you know, he was a good guy. He was a good

09:11.020 --> 09:11.801
guy. And when J.D. called up, he said, be sure and 
bring Dr. Holland with you. And we got down there,

09:16.440 --> 09:21.180
and he said, oh, he just welcomed with Omar, and he 
said, can I give you a hug?

09:25.800 --> 09:30.600
And I was sure glad that, even though I could have 
just sat on my butt and not taught anything as

09:30.580 --> 09:37.940
department head, I continued to teach because 
those are the kind of relationships that you, you

09:37.920 --> 09:41.900
don't realize how many of them are out there until 
you get out there. We had a big class at the end of the

09:41.880 --> 09:43.760
M.T. and we were able to pay for a whole class on the 
5th of August. And I figured, since we had just

09:47.580 --> 09:53.960
started, I could do whatever I wanted. But I wanted 
to stay out of the classroom. So I had never really

09:56.660 --> 10:03.300
found any students that were interested in 
teaching the math The internet was a big thing. I

10:04.280 --> 10:05.301
could learn something new. It's hard to do a few 
things a day without talking to people. Because

10:07.320 --> 10:08.441
they're scattered all over. Let's see. Did you 
ever have, you know, I talked with this old boy that

10:08.766 --> 10:10.660
wasn't even one of our students. 55, 56, down at 
Dow. And he told me that when he saw that I was going

10:15.460 --> 10:20.900
to give the talk, he said, I don't think that could 
be the same Dr. Holland that I knew and taught me

10:25.660 --> 10:27.320
that course. But now he's an old man. Well, he said 
that at that time he was about 20, 21, and I was about

10:31.680 --> 10:38.360
30. And he thought that that looked awfully old to 
him then, 30 years old. But you run across, I've run

10:44.980 --> 10:47.700
across a lot of people that I've taught in graduate 
extension courses. So I think, actually, well,

10:50.360 --> 10:53.700
you go back to the Bible. What was the teacher? And 
this is what people don't think about, that

10:59.880 --> 11:03.220
teaching probably is the most honorable of all 
professions and the most important. And it's the

11:06.360 --> 11:08.300
way to have the most, the most influential 
influence. Did you ever have, in your years as a

11:10.300 --> 11:16.220
faculty member and or department head, did you 
ever have a legislator or a regent attempt to

11:16.640 --> 11:25.120
intervene and twist your arm? No, the closest I 
came was this little boy that gave the money for the

11:31.220 --> 11:32.701
business administration bill. John Blocker. 
Blocker. In the early 70s, we were having this

11:35.740 --> 11:39.200
energy. And so I'd set up this energy symposium. 
And I'd been down in Mexico, and I'd visited the old

11:43.680 --> 11:46.300
boy. De La Pena was, he was in charge of all 
purchasing for PMAX. In the last four years is

11:54.040 --> 11:56.700
where you rake in the money. You know, you slip some 
out of all of it. And let's see, I can't forget,

11:59.540 --> 12:04.890
remember the other guy's name. He was in the 
University of Texas. He was in charge of all

12:06.110 --> 12:07.491
production. And so. So when Blocker, for some 
reason, he heard about it. So he sent his plane down

12:15.400 --> 12:17.520
to the King. They stopped over at the King Ranch and 
went hunting down there a little bit, I think. And

12:22.760 --> 12:26.420
then Blocker sent his plane over to pick them up. 
And he also put them in the quarters for the Board of

12:26.920 --> 12:32.440
Regents over here at the MSC. And then that night, 
he wanted to introduce the

12:32.660 --> 12:40.740
fellow from Texas. He was in charge of all the oil. 
And here's what he said. He says, this is a great

12:45.560 --> 12:47.820
moment in history. Mexico has just discovered 
they've got all of this oil. And he said, they need

12:54.070 --> 12:55.651
to sell it. And there's not a better person to sell 
it than I am.

13:03.160 --> 13:05.300
That was the way he introduced it. And it wasn't, 
well, a year or two after they were chasing both of

13:05.640 --> 13:13.300
those all over the country, they were wanting to 
know where they'd head out to. Because. Because

13:13.482 --> 13:16.560
they'd absconded with some money down there. But 
that was one of the cases where I did have a Board of

13:16.920 --> 13:23.740
Directors member involved. Actually, I knew Dr. 
Boyd, but not all that well. We used to go fishing

13:27.980 --> 13:31.040
down there, and I'd talk to him. He knew. But I 
wasn't around him enough just to know him

13:33.480 --> 13:37.640
personally like I did Rudder. All right, now, I've 
about finished questions. Do you think of any

13:41.480 --> 13:44.060
topics that we should have talked about? We 
didn't. I don't. It seems to me like we've covered

13:45.960 --> 13:48.200
an awful lot. All right. Let's see. One item is to 
say if you have at this point or any time in the

13:51.590 --> 14:04.070
future any papers, memorabilia, or anything else 
that you are going to dispose of, I beg you, please

14:04.410 --> 14:10.030
hand it over to the A&M Archives so it'll be 
preserved forever. I think I've thrown about

14:11.850 --> 14:14.190
everything away already. Well, that's what I 
worry about is things getting thrown away because

14:14.170 --> 14:23.170
it is the accumulation that can help give a more 
clear picture of A&M. But, you know, we've had so

14:24.630 --> 14:29.530
little space at this place that we just didn't have 
room enough to store it. But, see, now, over in the

14:29.630 --> 14:32.550
archives with the Cushing, they do. Okay, next to 
last question. Let's make believe that someone

14:37.650 --> 14:44.500
gives you a check for a million dollars, and it's a 
good, solid check, and there's only one

14:44.480 --> 14:45.781
requirement. You have to pass it on to Texas A&M, 
and you decide what they should do with it. In other

14:51.540 --> 14:55.080
words, if you could give A&M a million dollars, 
what would you want them to do with it? Oh, I think it

14:55.940 --> 14:59.360
should. I'm not sure about other departments, but 
one of the places where we need money more than

15:00.840 --> 15:06.300
anywhere else, and it's the hardest raised, and 
that is graduate fellowships. You can raise money

15:13.170 --> 15:15.610
for undergraduate fellowships. Because most 
people can associate with them that were

15:16.150 --> 15:21.010
undergraduates that have gone out and done well. 
But the ones that's hardest is the graduate

15:21.210 --> 15:31.950
students and the, well, that one wouldn't get very 
far on chairs as far as that goes, but I'd say with

15:31.930 --> 15:38.270
that amount of money that this would be helped with 
graduate fellowships so that we could attract

15:38.250 --> 15:41.950
some real good students. And I'd like to see them up 
the ante for USC. Well,

15:45.850 --> 15:50.810
I'm not sure I know what you mean there. That gives 
them a little better salary, and we do foreigners

15:50.890 --> 15:57.050
to encourage more of our own citizens to go to 
graduate school. You're saying the stipend for

15:57.990 --> 16:00.210
graduate students. The stipend for graduate 
students. There's nothing in the world for us

16:02.330 --> 16:08.990
wrong with us being partial to our own students. 
And so we don't have to treat them exactly like we

16:09.790 --> 16:13.950
treat the foreigners. And so just to get some of 
ours in. They are so up against it that they'll come

16:17.510 --> 16:23.050
here under a different set of circumstances, and 
our own people will. But we want our own people in

16:23.110 --> 16:28.190
the, we want them involved. And so we don't, in the 
industry and in the research, running the

16:28.170 --> 16:33.530
research organizations, and so we need to get 
those kind of people in graduate school and not all

16:33.730 --> 16:38.190
foreigners. Now, the Saudis didn't mind at all 
doing things like that because I was over there

16:38.970 --> 16:43.770
once, and the king was having trouble with all the 
young Saudis. The Saudis wanted to get out and

16:47.510 --> 16:50.270
drive automobiles up and down the beach. And a lot 
of them got into driving cabs. And so while I was

16:53.590 --> 17:01.310
there, he came out with a proclamation that no 
Saudi man could drive a cab until he was 30 years

16:53.590 --> 17:01.310
old. He figured by then the fever would have worn 
off because they were looking at, they wanted

17:08.070 --> 17:14.010
their people to go to get an education and help run 
that country. And so I think we've got to do the same

17:14.840 --> 17:17.920
thing. All right, last question. After 50, more 
than 50 years of service here, what feelings do you

17:21.160 --> 17:26.960
have in your heart for Texas A&M? Well, I think it's 
a great school, and I think that what we should

17:27.860 --> 17:35.060
have, one of the things I see wrong with hiring so 
many, we always think we have to hire an outsider,

17:41.980 --> 17:46.080
but a lot of times it's really I have a bag we'll 
travel. And I think that we have, we need to hire an

17:46.910 --> 17:48.830
outsider. And I think that we need more people 
coming up through organization like they have in

17:49.350 --> 17:53.930
companies to where you know the culture and you 
have more dedicated people that will be, do what

18:00.090 --> 18:07.390
they think is best for the university and not 
always career oriented what's best for me. And so I

18:08.050 --> 18:13.490
think that's one of the things that I would say is 
that we do need more of that so that we will get

18:13.470 --> 18:18.230
people who are dedicated and I think people have 
stayed with it a long time, are dedicated and want

18:18.210 --> 18:21.270
to see the best for A&M.

